choices.text:
fitting into American culture in what was called the’wretched hive,’ a dark reflection of the natural curves of my curls and qua as the lone bearer of my ethnicity and my wacky evening dress was sometimes disrupted between uncoordinated parts and scars my tangled and ebony figure. My parents ran many social projects with Jumoke Hamilton, Oswald and others, when I was 10, Gwen Hamilton died. I grew up very close to her. She regularly wrote poems and stories. She often made dresses for me. For her funeral, I chose a blue and gray suit with a matching scarf covering my head to pay tribute to her color.

“Mahadevi (formally Gwen) told that she knew the art of braiding when I was too young to do it. It was traumatic, I’ve tied myself up and even played with myself as a kid. I refused my hair and worked non-stop to control its proportions. Growing up Black in America, it was like paying the most expensive tuition in the world. It made me realize that colors and hair have spiritual qualities. When I was 12, I learned that Beads Art is an African spiritual process. I became a House of Abundance worshipper and I was able to use colored beads and cotton fabrics, cloth scraps, hair, shells, beaded bracelets and necklaces, claw claps and usually worn with my clothes. Mahadevi realized the power of accessories but couldn’t afford the materials that I now know can be expensive
